Some men in Libya refuse to undergo court mediation and want to punish the woman legally, putting barriers in her path to freedom. They have been making attempts to slow down the divorce process including embarking on trials to dissolve the mahr/bride price that was paid by the groom prior to the marriage itself. There have been five cases so far, with one man looking to make off with the sum of £80,000.

The worst part about men fighting the divorce is its effects on the wives who were driven to divorce by their husbands in the first place due to the psychological abuse they were subjected to.

Themarriage is one of the few civil and human rights that women fought for in Libya. The battle is by no means over, and they are still facing inequalities and discrimination on a daily basis
